    </button>
    <div class="faq-a" id="performance-based-pricing-high-risk-high-reward"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Performance-based pricing ties fees directly to outcomes. Common structures include cost per lead ($50–$500), cost per acquisition ($500+), or revenue share (5–25% of new revenue generated).</p></div></div>
  </div>
  <div class="faq-item">
    <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="your-seo-team-99-month-30-optimized-articles-publi">
      <span class="faq-q-text">Your SEO team. $99/month. 30 optimized articles, published automatically. No agency markup, no long contracts. Start for $1 → Chapter 5: Hybrid and Emerging Models The fastest-growing trend in agency pricing is combining multiple models into hybrid structures. These balance predictability for the agency with performance incentives for the client. Hybrid Models in Practice Common hybrid structures include: Base retainer + performance bonus: $3,000–$5,000/mo + $250–$500 per qualified lead Base fee + percentage of ad spend: $8,000/mo base + 8% above $50K spend threshold Retainer + revenue share: $15,000/mo flat + 2.8% of attributed revenue According to 2026 industry data, 27% of top agencies now use some form of hybrid pricing. That number is rising as clients demand more accountability and agencies seek more upside. Productized Services Productized services are pre-packaged, standardized offerings with fixed deliverables and pricing. Examples include: "Technical SEO audit, $5,000 flat, delivered in 10 business days" "Google Business Profile optimization, $1,500 one-time" "Content cluster build, 10 articles, $8,000 flat" Productized packages deliver 55–70% margins for repeatable work. They reduce negotiation time, eliminate custom scoping for every sale, and let clients buy without a sales call. The key is picking services that are genuinely repeatable. If every engagement requires custom strategy, productization will fail. Usage-Based and AI-Native Pricing AI-assisted delivery is creating new pricing models. Some agencies now charge per deliverable rather than per hour or per month. A blog post costs $180. A landing page costs $350. The client pays for what they use. This model works when AI tools reduce delivery time by 20–30%. The agency earns the same revenue in fewer hours, widening margins. The client gets transparent pricing tied to output, not time. Subscription + usage hybrids are also emerging: $1,500/mo base for core work + $120 per additional deliverable. This gives the agency a revenue floor while capturing upside from high-need clients. Capacity-Based "Creative Pods" An emerging model for high-velocity B2B teams is the creative pod. Instead of selling deliverables, the agency sells embedded team capacity: Starter pod: $10,000–$20,000/mo Full pod: $40,000–$75,000+/mo The client gets weekly sprints with flexible priority allocation. The agency gets predictable recurring revenue without defining every deliverable upfront. Chapter 6: How to Calculate Your True Costs Most agencies that undercharge do not know what they actually cost to run. They set prices based on what competitors charge or what feels reasonable. And discover months later that they are losing money on their best clients. Pricing starts with a single hard number: your minimum sustainable hourly rate. The Base Hourly Cost Formula (Total Monthly Salaries + Total Monthly Overhead) / Total Monthly Billable Hours = Base Hourly Cost</span>
