  <div class="faq-item">
    <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="is-performance-based-pricing-risky-for-agencies">
      <span class="faq-q-text">Is performance-based pricing risky for agencies?</span>
      <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
    </button>
    <div class="faq-a" id="is-performance-based-pricing-risky-for-agencies"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Yes. Performance-based pricing puts agency revenue at the mercy of factors the agency does not fully control. Algorithm updates, client site performance, seasonal demand shifts. Use performance bonuses layered on top of a base retainer rather than as the sole pricing mechanism. Reserve pure performance deals for accounts where you have strong historical data, full execution control, and a client relationship built on demonstrated results.</p></div></div>
  </div>
  <div class="faq-item">
    <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="how-do-i-transition-from-hourly-to-value-based-pri">
      <span class="faq-q-text">How do I transition from hourly to value-based pricing?</span>
      <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
    </button>
    <div class="faq-a" id="how-do-i-transition-from-hourly-to-value-based-pri"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Start with one client who has documented ROI from your work. Calculate the business value you have delivered: leads generated, revenue attributed, cost savings achieved. Propose a new structure at 10–15% of that monthly value. If the client accepts, you have a case study for the next one. If they decline, you still have the hourly relationship. Transition one client at a time. Never switch your entire book of business at once.</p></div></div>
  </div>
  <div class="faq-item">
    <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="what-is-a-healthy-profit-margin-for-an-agency">
      <span class="faq-q-text">What is a healthy profit margin for an agency?</span>
      <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
    </button>
    <div class="faq-a" id="what-is-a-healthy-profit-margin-for-an-agency"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Healthy agencies run 45–65% gross margin on delivery. Below 35% signals underpricing or overstaffing. Net profit margin after all overhead typically ranges from 15–25% for established agencies. If your gross margin is below 40%, raise prices or reduce delivery costs before taking on new clients.</p></div></div>
  </div>
</div>

<p>Agency pricing is the foundation every other business decision rests on. Set it correctly and you can hire, grow, and serve clients at a high level. Set it wrong and every new client adds pressure instead of margin.</p>
<p>Pick one primary pricing model, calculate your true cost floor, package your services into clear tiers, and build annual rate adjustments into your contracts from day one. That is the difference between an agency that compounds and one that grinds.</p>
